 HARARE - Widespread protests are expected throughout Zimbabwe on Friday despite emerging reports of abductions and torture of activists. The country's trade unions and the opposition Movement for Democratic Change party, are protesting austerity measures. The MDC has stressed demonstrations will be peaceful. READ: MDC, Zimbabwe trade unions planning protests They'll be the first since January rallies against fuel hikes ended in deadly clashes with police. MDC's Secretary General Chalton Hwende stated the group will be appealing to the High Court in Harare to allow the protests to legally proceed. Hwende said the government has abducted leaders of the protests and has been preventing people from moving around the city. He said, "this Mnangagwa is leading a terrorist government that is abducting people at night, that is torturing people all to prevent them from exercising their constitutional rights."